internal_merge

private void internal_merge(org.w3c.dom.Element lElt,
                            org.w3c.dom.Element rElt,
                            org.w3c.dom.Element resElt)
                     throws ShutdownException
Merges two elements together and puts the result into a pre-existing result element. This is used internally and captures both the accumulate and merge functionality.

Parameters:
lElt - "left" element to be merged
rElt - "right" element to be merged
resElt - Result element - this elt will be modified and upon return will contain the result of the merge Note - attrs are added to resElt and any existing attrs will be preserved (needed for accumulate)
Throws:
ShutdownException

mergeAttributes

private void mergeAttributes()
                      throws ShutdownException
Function to merge the attributes of two elements. One element is always dominant - that element's content is put in result and if the two elements have any of the same attributes - the attribute value from the dominant element is taken. As for attributes that appear in one element, but not in the other, several options are supported - left outer "join", right outer "join", inner "join", and outer "join" The result element is modified appropriately. Maybe should turn this into a HashJoin class...

Throws:
ShutdownException

                                 java.util.ArrayList deletedAttrs)
Process all attributes in a map from a side. For some reason we know that these attrs do not have a match on the other side - this can be because the other attrsMap is null or because all matching attrs have already been processed

Parameters:
attrsMap - The hash map of the attributes to be processed

processOuterAttr

private void processOuterAttr(org.w3c.dom.Attr attr,
                              boolean includeOuter,
                              boolean isResult,
                              java.util.ArrayList resultAttrs,
                              java.util.ArrayList deletedAttrs)
Function to process an attribute which doesn't have a match in the other element. Call this an "outer" attribute as in outer join terminology - which is basically what is going on here

Parameters:
attr - The attribute to be processed
includeOuter - Indicates if this attr should be included in result even if there is no matching attr on other side
isResult - Indicates if elt is the actual result elt or not
resultAttrs - The place to put any attrs that should be added to the result (use a list to avoid haloween problem-like effects
elt - The element associated with this attr
